{"key":"post-12966240","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12966240</id>\n<content>I haven't been following this thread closely, but just saw something above that freaked me the hell out.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;Do NOT spray insecticides on your mushrooms&lt;/b&gt;.&amp;nbsp; After harvest, which you should have done by now anyway, all you have to do is bump the mushrooms on a table a few times and the bugs will get knocked off.&amp;nbsp; We grow a lot of outdoor mushrooms and they're always covered with small bugs of one kind or another.&amp;nbsp; They're easy to get rid of as said above.&amp;nbsp; Mushrooms absorb water, so any water based pesticide will be absorbed right into the fruit.&amp;nbsp; I doubt seriously anyone wants to eat nerve toxins.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It's bad enough when apple growers spray their fruits, but in that case the toxins stay on the surface where 'most' can be rinsed off.&amp;nbsp; Not so with mushrooms which will absorb the poison and then transfer it directly to your liver when you eat them.&amp;nbsp; Think about that while you're tripping and it won't be pleasant.&amp;nbsp; If you've already sprayed the damn things, toss them out.&amp;nbsp; The spray is a thousand times worse than any bug.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12966263</next>\n<prev>12966161</prev>\n<first>12952420</first>\n<last>13028034</last>\n<when>1280337950</when>\n<utime>07/28/10 08:25 PM</utime>\n</post>"}